  "tutorialGotIt": "Got it!",
  "tutorialListen": "Listen",
  "primerReadingTitle": "Reading notes",
  "primerReadingStaff": "Music is written on five lines called a staff. Notes sit on the lines and in the spaces between them.",
  "primerReadingHigher": "The higher a note sits on the staff, the higher it sounds. Tap Listen and hear these notes climb!",
  "primerReadingNames": "Every note has a letter name: A B C D E F G. This one is E — tap Listen to hear it.",
  "primerValuesTitle": "How long is a note?",
  "primerValuesWhole": "A note's shape shows how LONG to hold it. This open oval with no stem is a whole note — a long sound (4 beats).",
  "primerValuesQuarter": "A filled note with a stem is a quarter note — one short beat. Four quarter notes last as long as one whole note.",
  "primerValuesRest": "A rest is a beat of SILENCE. Count it in your head, but don't play. Tap Listen to hear a beat of rest.",
  "primerMeasuresTitle": "Filling a measure",
  "primerMeasuresBars": "Music is split into measures (bars) by barlines. A time signature like 4/4 means each measure holds 4 beats.",
  "primerMeasuresFill": "Fill each measure so the beats add up. Four quarter notes make 4 beats — one full 4/4 measure.",
  "primerMeasuresHalf": "A half note lasts 2 beats, so two half notes also fill a 4/4 measure.",
  "primerScalesTitle": "What is a scale?",
  "primerScalesLadder": "A scale is a ladder of notes climbing step by step. This is C major: C D E F G A B C.",
  "primerScalesMajor": "A major scale sounds bright and cheerful. Listen to C major climb up.",
  "primerScalesMinor": "A minor scale sounds darker, a little sad. Listen to A minor.",
  "primerChordsTitle": "Building a chord",
  "primerChordsStack": "A chord is notes played at the SAME time. Stack three notes a gap apart and you get a triad — here, C E G.",
  "primerChordsColour": "A major triad sounds bright; a minor triad sounds softer and sadder. Listen to both.",
  "primerChordsArpeggio": "You can also play a chord one note at a time, bottom to top — that's an arpeggio.",
  "primerHarmonyTitle": "Chords have jobs",
  "primerHarmonyHome": "One chord feels like HOME — settled and finished. We call it the Tonic. Listen: this is C major, home base.",
  "primerHarmonyPull": "Other chords pull AWAY and want to return home. The Dominant tugs the hardest — hear how it leans right back to home.",
  "primerHarmonyCadence": "When chords travel home → away → home, that little journey to a resting point is a cadence. Listen to the whole trip.",
  "primerCompositionTitle": "Make a melody",
  "primerCompositionJourney": "A melody is a little journey of notes — some step up, some come down. Hum along as it rises and falls!",
  "primerCompositionQuestion": "A tune can ask a QUESTION — it stops high up in the air, sounding unfinished, as if it's waiting.",
  "primerCompositionAnswer": "…then it gives an ANSWER, coming back down to rest at home. A question and its answer make a phrase.",
  "primerCelloTitle": "Your four strings",
  "primerCelloStrings": "The cello has four strings. From low to high they are C, G, D, A — the lowest string is the thickest.",
  "primerCelloBass": "Cello notes live on the bass clef, the staff for low sounds. This deep note is C, your thickest string.",
  "primerCelloFinger": "Press a finger onto a string to shorten it and the note gets higher. The tuner listens and shows if you're spot on.",
  "primerGuitarTitle": "Six strings and tab",
  "primerGuitarStrings": "A guitar has six strings. From low (thick) to high (thin): E, A, D, G, B, E — yes, an E at each end!",
  "primerGuitarTab": "Guitar can be written as tab: six lines, one per string. A number is the fret to press; 0 means play the open string.",
  "primerGuitarPlay": "Play the note shown, or strum along. The thinner the string, the higher it sings — from low E up to high E.",
  "primerSongsTitle": "Follow the tune",
  "primerSongsPick": "Pick a song you know. The screen shows its tune as a line of notes, read left to right.",
  "primerSongsMarker": "A marker slides along the tune. Sing or play each note as it reaches the line — like following a bouncing ball.",
  "primerKeyboardTitle": "The piano keys",
  "primerKeyboardWhite": "The white keys are named A B C D E F G, repeating up the whole piano. The black keys sit in little groups of two and three.",
  "primerKeyboardFindC": "Find C: it's the white key just to the LEFT of every group of TWO black keys. From C, climb up C D E F G A B C.",
  "primerKeyboardHands": "Piano music uses two staves at once: the top staff for your right hand, the bottom staff for your left. Hear both together.",
  "primerTransposeTitle": "Read one note, hear another",
  "primerTransposeSame": "Most instruments sound the note they read. Read a C, hear a C — simple.",
  "primerTransposeShift": "But some are ‘transposing’: a trumpet in B♭ reads a C yet a B♭ comes out — a little lower. This game does that swap for you.",
  "primerDrumsTitle": "Reading drums",
  "primerDrumsWhat": "Drums don't play high and low tunes — a drum just goes THUMP or TSS. So drum music shows WHICH drum and WHEN, not a pitch.",
  "primerDrumsLines": "Each line and space is a different drum: low down is the bass drum you kick, higher up are the snare and cymbals. Read left to right and play the beat.",
  "primerBassTitle": "The bass clef",
  "primerBassClef": "This low staff is the bass clef (the F-clef). A cello or a left hand reads here. Its lines and spaces spell different notes than the treble clef.",
  "primerBassMiddleC": "Middle C — the note in the middle of the piano — sits just above the bass staff, on its own little ledger line.",
  "primerLedgerTitle": "Ledger lines",
  "primerLedgerMiddleC": "When a note won't fit on the five lines, we add a tiny extra line just for it — a ledger line. Middle C hangs on one, right below the treble staff.",
  "primerLedgerHigh": "The higher a note climbs above the staff, the more ledger lines it needs. Count them like the rungs of a ladder.",
  "primerAccidentalsTitle": "Sharps and flats",
  "primerAccidentalsSharp": "A sharp ♯ in front of a note lifts it up by the smallest step, a semitone. C♯ is a hair higher than C.",
  "primerAccidentalsFlat": "A flat ♭ lowers a note by a semitone. D♭ is the very same key as C♯ — it just leans down from D.",
  "primerSpacingTitle": "Close and open",
  "primerSpacingClose": "In CLOSE position the top three voices are bunched together — the highest and the tenor sit within one octave.",
  "primerSpacingOpen": "In OPEN position the top voices are spread out — the highest note is more than an octave above the tenor.",
  "primerStepSkipTitle": "Steps and skips",
  "primerStepSkipStep": "A STEP moves to the next-door note — a line to the space touching it, one letter along: C to D.",
  "primerStepSkipSkip": "A SKIP jumps over one — a line straight to the next line: C to E. Skips sound bouncier than steps.",
  "primerIntervalsTitle": "How far apart?",
  "primerIntervalsCount": "The distance between two notes is an interval. Count the letters including both ends: C to E is C-D-E — a 3rd.",
  "primerIntervalsWide": "The wider the gap, the bigger the number. C up to G is a 5th: C-D-E-F-G.",
  "primerIntervalsEar": "Narrow intervals sound close and gentle; wide ones sound open and bold. Listen to a small gap, then a big one.",
  "primerIntervalsSong": "You already know intervals from songs! A cuckoos call — \u201cKuck-uck\u201d — is a falling minor 3rd. \u201cAlle meine Entchen\u201d starts with a major 2nd going up.",
  "primerKeySigTitle": "Key signatures",
  "primerKeySigWhat": "Instead of marking every sharp, we write them once at the very start — a key signature. It applies to the whole piece. This is G major: one sharp, F♯.",
  "primerKeySigCompare": "C major has no sharps or flats at all. Listen to C major — every note is a plain white key.",
  "primerTimeSigTitle": "Time signatures",
  "primerTimeSigFour": "The two numbers at the start are the time signature. The top number is how many beats fill each measure — 4 means a steady four.",
  "primerTimeSigThree": "Change the top number to 3 and each measure has three beats — the gentle swing of a waltz. Count 1-2-3, 1-2-3.",
  "primerChartTitle": "Chord symbols",
  "primerChartMajor": "Above a tune you'll see chord symbols. A plain letter means a major chord: ‘C’ tells you to play a C major chord.",
  "primerChartMinor": "A small ‘m’ after the letter means minor: ‘Am’ is A minor — the same family, but a softer, sadder colour.",
  "primerUpbeatTitle": "Starting on the upbeat",
  "primerUpbeatDownbeat": "Most tunes start on beat 1 — the strong downbeat. Count ‘1-2-3-4’ and begin on the 1.",
  "primerUpbeatUpbeat": "An upbeat (or pickup) starts with a note or two BEFORE the first barline, leading into beat 1. Listen — the tune leans in.",
  "primerEnharmonicTitle": "The same note, two names",
  "primerEnharmonicSame": "This piano key can be written as F♯ or G♭ — the very same sound, spelled two ways. They are ‘enharmonic’ twins.",
  "primerEnharmonicTwins": "So F♯ and G♭ sound identical. Other twins: C♯=D♭, D♯=E♭, G♯=A♭, A♯=B♭.",
  "primerExpressionTitle": "Fast or slow, loud or soft",
  "primerExpressionTempo": "Expression is HOW you play. One part is the speed (tempo): listen to this phrase slow, then fast.",
  "primerExpressionDynamics": "The other part is how loud (dynamics): the same phrase soft (p), then loud (f). Charades asks you to name what you heard.",
  "primerTempoTitle": "How fast? Tempo words",
  "primerTempoSlow": "At the top of a piece an Italian word gives the speed. Largo is very slow, Adagio is slow. Listen — these four notes are Adagio.",
  "primerTempoFast": "Allegro is fast, Presto very fast. The same four notes, just quicker — listen to the difference.",
  "primerDynamicsTitle": "How loud? p and f",
  "primerDynamicsSoft": "Dynamics tell you how loud to play. p (piano) means soft — and pp (pianissimo) is very soft. Listen: this is piano.",
  "primerDynamicsLoud": "f (forte) means loud, and ff (fortissimo) very loud. The same notes again — now forte.",
  "primerDottedTitle": "The dot that adds half",
  "primerDottedPlain": "A half note lasts 2 beats. Count ‘1-2’ while it rings.",
  "primerDottedDotted": "A dot after a note adds HALF its value again: 2 beats + 1 = a dotted half note of 3 beats. Count ‘1-2-3’.",
  "primerRestsTitle": "Silence has length",
  "primerRestsSilence": "A rest is silence — and you count it, just like a note. Here it goes play, rest, play, rest — one beat each.",
  "primerRestsMatch": "Every note value has a matching rest. A half note rings for 2 beats; a half rest is 2 beats of silence.",
  "primerCurveTitle": "Ties and slurs",
  "primerCurveTie": "A TIE joins two notes of the SAME pitch. Don't play the second one — hold the first right through both. C tied to C is one long C.",
  "primerCurveSlur": "A SLUR curves over DIFFERENT pitches. Play them smoothly, joined with no gap between them — that's legato.",
  "primerArticulationTitle": "How to play the note",
  "primerArticulationStaccato": "A dot above or below the notehead is staccato: play it short and detached, with air after it. (Careful — a dot BESIDE the note makes it longer instead!)",
  "primerArticulationAccent": "A wedge > is an accent: give that note an extra push so it stands out from its neighbours.",
  "primerBeamTitle": "Flags and beams",
  "primerBeamFlag": "A lone eighth note wears a flag on its stem. Here a rest splits the eighths apart, so each one keeps its own flag.",
  "primerBeamBeam": "When eighths share a beat they are joined by a BEAM instead of flags — the same sound, just tidier to read.",
  "primerToneTitle": "Half steps and whole steps",
  "primerToneHalf": "A half step (semitone) is the smallest step on the keyboard — neighbours with nothing between. E to F is a half step: no black key between them.",
  "primerToneWhole": "A whole step is two half steps. C to D is a whole step — there IS a black key between them.",
  "primerClefTitle": "Which clef?",
  "primerClefTreble": "The treble clef (G-clef) curls around the line that means G. It is used for higher notes — right hand, flute, violin.",
  "primerClefBass": "The bass clef (F-clef) puts two dots around the line that means F. It is used for lower notes — left hand, cello, bass.",
  "primerVoicesTitle": "Four voices at once",
  "primerVoicesChord": "A choir sings four lines together: Soprano (highest), Alto, Tenor, Bass (lowest). Sounded at the same time they make a chord.",
  "primerVoicesFollow": "To read one voice, follow only its line: the soprano is the top note, the bass the bottom. Listen — top voice, then bottom.",
  "primerDirectionTitle": "Up or down?",
  "primerDirectionUp": "When a melody climbs, every note is higher than the one before — on the staff the notes walk upward, and the sound rises.",
  "primerDirectionDown": "When it falls, every note is lower than the one before — the notes walk down the staff, and the sound sinks.",
  "primerSameDiffTitle": "Same or different?",
  "primerSameDiffSame": "Two notes at the SAME pitch sound exactly alike — like an echo. On the staff they sit in the very same place.",
  "primerSameDiffDifferent": "If the second note is even one step higher or lower, it is different — and it sits somewhere else on the staff. Listen: C then D.",
  "primerCountTitle": "How many notes?",
  "primerCountThree": "Listen and count how many separate notes go by. Here there are three — count one for each new sound.",
  "primerCountFour": "Now four. They come quickly, so count each one the moment it arrives.",
  "primerAccentTitle": "Strong and weak beats",
  "primerAccentCount": "In 4/4 you count 1-2-3-4 over and over. Beat 1 is the STRONG beat — the one you tap hardest. Beats 2, 3 and 4 are lighter.",
  "primerAccentThree": "The meter decides which beat is strong. In 3/4 you count 1-2-3, and the 1 is strong again — that's the lilt of a waltz.",
  "primerSeventhTitle": "Adding a seventh",
  "primerSeventhTriad": "A triad is three notes — take one, skip one, take the next, skip one: C, E, G. That is C major, and it sounds settled.",
  "primerSeventhAdd": "Add one MORE note the same way (skip one, take the next) and you get a seventh chord: C E G B♭. It sounds restless — as if it wants to move on.",
  "primerRomanTitle": "Numbering the chords",
  "primerRomanDegree": "Number the notes of the scale 1 to 7. Build a chord on each step and name it with a Roman numeral. On step 1 of C major sits C E G — chord I.",
  "primerRomanCase": "CAPITALS mean a major chord (I, IV, V); small letters mean minor (ii, iii, vi). On step 2 of C major sits D F A — chord ii, D minor.",
  "primerCadenceTitle": "How a phrase ends",
  "primerCadenceFull": "A cadence is how a phrase ends — like the end of a sentence. Ending on the HOME chord sounds finished, like a full stop. Listen: away, then home.",
  "primerCadenceHalf": "Ending on a different chord leaves it hanging, like a question mark — your ear expects more to come. Listen: home, then away.",
  "primerPhraseTitle": "Question and answer",
  "primerPhraseQuestion": "Music comes in phrases, like sentences. This one climbs away and stops in the air — it sounds like a QUESTION.",
  "primerPhraseAnswer": "The answering phrase comes back to the note the tune started from — its home note. That is why it sounds finished.",
  "primerBowTitle": "Which way the bow goes",
  "primerBowDown": "⊓ means DOWN-bow: pull the bow from the frog (your hand) toward the tip. It's the heavier direction, so it suits strong beats.",
  "primerBowUp": "∨ means UP-bow: push from the tip back toward the frog. It's lighter — good for upbeats and lead-ins.",
  "primerTenorTitle": "The tenor clef",
  "primerTenorC": "The tenor clef is a C-clef: the middle of the sign points straight at middle C. Wherever the sign sits, that line IS middle C.",
  "primerTenorWhy": "Cellos and trombones use it for their higher notes — it keeps them on the staff instead of piling up ledger lines above the bass clef.",
  "primerGrandTitle": "Two staves, two hands",
  "primerGrandTop": "The piano writes on a GRAND STAFF: two staves joined by a brace. The top one is treble — usually your right hand.",
  "primerGrandBottom": "The bottom one is bass — usually your left hand. Middle C sits in the gap between the two staves, on its own little ledger line.",
